---
// src/pages/blog.astro
import MainLayout from "../../layouts/MainLayout.astro";
---

<MainLayout title="UI/UX Workshop Highlights" isBlogPost={true}>
  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-8 md:px-16 py-10 mt-8 mb-16">
    <h1
      class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white my-6 text-center"
    >
      UI/UX Workshop Highlights: A Personal Reflection
    </h1>

    <nav class="mb-10 flex justify-center">
      <div
        class="w-full max-w-md bg-indigo-50 dark:bg-gray-800 border border-indigo-200 dark:border-gray-700 rounded-xl shadow-md p-5"
      >
        <h2
          class="text-lg font-semibold text-indigo-900 dark:text-indigo-200 mb-3 text-center tracking-wide"
        >
          Table of Contents
        </h2>
        <ul
          class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-2 text-indigo-700 dark:text-indigo-300 text-base"
        >
          <li>
            <a
              href="#why-i-attended"
              class="hover:text-indigo-900 dark:hover:text-white transition-colors duration-150 font-medium"
              >Why I Attended</a
            >
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="#what-i-learned"
              class="hover:text-indigo-900 dark:hover:text-white transition-colors duration-150 font-medium"
              >What I Learned</a
            >
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="#branding-lessons"
              class="hover:text-indigo-900 dark:hover:text-white transition-colors duration-150 font-medium"
              >Lessons on Branding</a
            >
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="#reflection"
              class="hover:text-indigo-900 dark:hover:text-white transition-colors duration-150 font-medium"
              >Final Thoughts</a
            >
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </nav>

    <h2
      id="why-i-attended"
      class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-200 mb-4 mt-10 scroll-mt-24"
    >
      Why I Attended
    </h2>
    <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-6">
      I signed up for this UI/UX seminar out of curiosity and a desire to
      sharpen my eye for design. Most of my work leans technical, but I've
      always known that the way something feels is just as important as how it
      works. I wanted to understand how designers think and how that thinking
      could influence how I build. What I didn't expect was how much the seminar
      would center on something even deeper: branding.
    </p>

    <h2
      id="what-i-learned"
      class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-200 mb-4 mt-10 scroll-mt-24"
    >
      What I Learned
    </h2>
    <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-6">
      The seminar packed a lot into a single day. We covered user research,
      interface design principles, and common usability pitfalls. But what stood
      out to me the most was how much of UI/UX is about intention. Every element
      on a screen sends a message. From color choices to spacing, all of these
      minor details matter in the grand scheme of things.
    </p>

    <h2
      id="branding-lessons"
      class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-200 mb-4 mt-10 scroll-mt-24"
    >
      Lessons on Branding
    </h2>
    <ul
      class="list-disc list-inside text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-6 space-y-2"
    >
      <li>
        <strong>Start with values.</strong> A brand isn't just a logo. It's a set
        of values expressed through design, words, and experience. Make those values
        clear first.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Clarity beats cleverness.</strong> Simpler interfaces feel more trustworthy.
        Remove friction, not personality.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Details create perception.</strong> The way a button animates, the
        tone of your 404 page, even your loading screen. All of it shapes how people
        feel about your product or personal brand.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Consistency matters.</strong> Whether you're building a portfolio
        or a startup, your visual language should stay cohesive. That builds recognition
        and trust.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2
      id="reflection"
      class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-200 mb-4 mt-10 scroll-mt-24"
    >
      Final Thoughts
    </h2>
    <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-6">
      I came to the workshop looking for design tips. I left with a new way of
      thinking about product development, storytelling, and identity. UI/UX
      isn't about making things pretty. It's about making them meaningful and
      making sure they say something real about who you are or what you're
      building.
    </p>

    <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
      UI/UX workshops are invaluable for anyone looking to improve their design
      skills. The lessons and experiences I gained continue to shape my work and
      inspire me to create more thoughtful, user-friendly products.
    </p>

    <div class="flex justify-between gap-4 mt-16">
      <a
        href="/blog/testing-slack-bots"
        class="text-indigo-700 dark:text-indigo-300 hover:underline font-medium flex items-center"
      >
        <svg
          class="mr-2 w-5 h-5"
          fill="none"
          stroke="currentColor"
          stroke-width="2"
          viewBox="0 0 24 24"
          ><path
            stroke-linecap="round"
            stroke-linejoin="round"
            d="M15 19l-7-7 7-7"></path></svg
        >
        Previous: Testing Slack Bots
      </a>
      <a
        href="/blog/astro-and-tailwind"
        class="text-indigo-700 dark:text-indigo-300 hover:underline font-medium flex items-center"
      >
        Next: Astro and Tailwind
        <svg
          class="ml-2 w-5 h-5"
          fill="none"
          stroke="currentColor"
          stroke-width="2"
          viewBox="0 0 24 24"
          ><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M9 5l7 7-7 7"
          ></path></svg
        >
      </a>
    </div>
  </div>
</MainLayout>
